## What happened

**DSA was removed on macOS.** Apple's security frameworks (Security.framework / CryptoKit) dropped DSA support years ago. .NET historically worked around this with an OpenSSL-based backend, but:

1. **`SYSLIB0030`** (introduced in .NET 7) marked `DSA.Create()` and related APIs as obsolete.
2. In .NET 11, the OpenSSL-based fallback on macOS was removed, so `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS.

Linux still works (uses OpenSSL directly), and Windows still works (uses CNG/CAPI).

## How to fix it

You have three options, depending on your constraints:

### Option 1 – Use BouncyCastle (recommended for legacy verification)

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

// Works on all platforms — pure managed code, no native dependency
ISigner signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA1withDSA");
signer.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);
signer.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
bool valid = signer.VerifySignature(signature);
```

This is the cleanest path for **legacy signature verification** — it's a fully managed implementation with no platform-specific crypto dependencies.

### Option 2 – Use OpenSSL interop on macOS only

If you want to keep using the built-in APIs on Linux/Windows and only fix macOS:

```csharp
using System.Runtime.InteropServices;
using System.Security.Cryptography;

#pragma warning disable SYSLIB0030 // DSA is obsolete
if (RuntimeInformation.IsOSPlatform(OSPlatform.OSX))
{
    // Use DSAOpenSsl with a Homebrew-installed OpenSSL
    using var dsa = new DSAOpenSsl(/* load key params */);
    // ...
}
else
{
    using var dsa = DSA.Create();
    // ...
}
#pragma warning restore SYSLIB0030
```

Requires `brew install openssl` on macOS build/runtime machines. Fragile — not recommended long-term.

### Option 3 – Migrate away from DSA entirely

If you control the signing side, re-sign with **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** (supported natively on all platforms). This eliminates the legacy algorithm dependency altogether.

## Summary

| Approach | Effort | Cross-platform | Long-term |
|---|---|---|---|
| BouncyCastle | Low | ✅ All platforms | ✅ Best for legacy verification |
| `DSAOpenSsl` interop | Medium | ⚠️ Needs OpenSSL on macOS | ❌ Still uses obsolete API |
| Migrate to ECDSA/Ed25519 | High | ✅ All platforms | ✅ Modern standard |

**Recommendation:** If you only need to *verify* existing legacy DSA signatures, go with **BouncyCastle**. It's pure managed code, works everywhere, and doesn't depend on any platform crypto provider.
